**What Nova Is**
Nova is a hybrid orchestrator. It prefers deterministic answers and explicit tools first, uses memory and local knowledge when it can ground a reply, and only falls back to the chat model after policy checks, context assembly, low-confidence blocking, and claim gating. You can see that layered order directly in [nova_http.py](nova_http.py#L3067) and [nova_http.py](nova_http.py#L2573).

It also has a separate operator/control plane. The same HTTP server exposes chat, control-room status, policy mutations, patch governance, operator macros, backend command decks, test-session control, and timeline telemetry. That control layer is composed from services such as [services/control_status.py](services/control_status.py), [services/runtime_control.py](services/runtime_control.py), [services/patch_control.py](services/patch_control.py), [services/operator_control.py](services/operator_control.py), and [services/runtime_timeline.py](services/runtime_timeline.py).

**How A Turn Works**
1. A browser or client post lands in [process_chat](nova_http.py#L3067). Nova binds the active user, loads the session object, and opens an action-ledger record.
2. The turn is preprocessed through shared chat-flow helpers in [http_chat_flow.py](http_chat_flow.py). Before any model call, Nova can block identity-only violations, clarify ambiguous numeric turns, and reject mixed turns that would confuse routing.
3. Nova asks the deterministic supervisor first. The rule engine in [supervisor.py](supervisor.py#L113) evaluates intent and handle phases, and HTTP is explicitly structured to mirror supervisor-owned behavior instead of inventing transport-only branches.
4. If no supervisor rule owns the turn, Nova can enter fulfillment mode through [services/fulfillment_flow.py](services/fulfillment_flow.py). That is the multi-path reasoning layer: it treats some prompts as ŌĆ£there are several real ways forwardŌĆØ rather than ŌĆ£produce one answer now.ŌĆØ
5. If fulfillment is not the right fit, Nova continues through deterministic side paths: smalltalk, identity learning, developer-profile learning, self-profile learning, location handling, declarative fact storage, follow-up consumption, and retrieval continuation.
6. Only after that does Nova enter the general reply engine in [_generate_chat_reply](nova_http.py#L2573). That engine applies truth hierarchy first, then hard answers, then planner/tool routes, then grounded lookups, then policy-gated LLM fallback.

The practical consequence is simple: Nova is designed to avoid unnecessary LLM use. Identity, policy, capability, action-history, location, weather, corrections, and several profile questions are intended to resolve before the model is asked.

**What Is Already In Place**
Nova already has strong runtime supervision. [nova_guard.py](nova_guard.py#L623) owns the guard loop, lock/PID identity, boot observation, stale artifact cleanup, restart backoff, and controlled shutdown. The guard supervises [nova_core.py](nova_core.py), while the HTTP plane inspects both through runtime status services rather than guessing from one signal.

Nova already has a memory stack, but it is segmented. General recall is stored in SQLite through [memory.py](memory.py), while identity facts live in JSON-backed files referenced by [services/nova_runtime_context.py](services/nova_runtime_context.py). Memory writes are filtered by heuristics in [services/memory_adapter.py](services/memory_adapter.py), and identity-only sessions are enforced by [services/identity_memory.py](services/identity_memory.py). Contextual identity learning has already been separated into [services/nova_memory_learning.py](services/nova_memory_learning.py).

Nova already has tooling and policy governance. Registered tools are wrapped by [services/tool_registry.py](services/tool_registry.py) and [services/tool_execution.py](services/tool_execution.py), which means execution is policy-checked and logged. Policy defaults and mutations live in [services/policy_manager.py](services/policy_manager.py). Web search, research, gather, Wikipedia, and StackExchange behavior are not free-form browser use; they are allowlisted, provider-aware, and policy-driven.

Nova already has a self-observation and evolution loop. [nova_core.py](nova_core.py#L9802) builds a pulse summary from promotion audit, behavior metrics, memory status, kidney status, patch activity, and autonomy state. [services/core_steward.py](services/core_steward.py) turns that into a maintenance score and queue. [autonomy_maintenance.py](autonomy_maintenance.py) runs subconscious packs, watches fallback-overuse pressure, can build micro-patch zips from promoted test definitions, and runs regression. [subconscious_runner.py](subconscious_runner.py) simulates live scenario families, extracts robust cracks, and writes generated session definitions. [kidney.py](kidney.py) then acts as lifecycle cleanup and archive/delete governance for previews, snapshots, quarantine, generated definitions, and temp runtime waste.

Nova already has a testing and promotion pipeline. Generated and saved session definitions are managed by [services/test_session_control.py](services/test_session_control.py). Release ledger status is summarized by [services/release_status.py](services/release_status.py). Patch application is not direct self-editing; it goes through preview, governance, eligibility checks, behavioral checks, snapshotting, and optionally apply/rollback via [services/nova_patching.py](services/nova_patching.py).

**My Straight Read**
The real core of Nova today is not the model. The real core is the routing contract.

That contract is:
- deterministic truth and supervisor ownership outrank LLM fallback
- sessions carry explicit conversation state and pending-action state
- memory is allowed, but filtered and scoped
- web/tool access is policy-bounded
- runtime health is supervised by a separate guard
- self-change is only supposed to happen through test generation, review, patch preview, and validated apply

That makes Nova closer to a supervised operating runtime than a simple assistant.

**Main Risks / Friction I See**
- [nova_core.py](nova_core.py) is still the central shell, so even with service extraction it remains the architectural gravity well.
- [nova_http.py](nova_http.py) is doing a lot. It is cleaner than before, but it is still the largest integration surface and the place where system behavior is easiest to accidentally fork.
- The autonomy and subconscious layers are real, but they are only as trustworthy as the generated-session and promotion pipeline. If that governance weakens, the system can create noise quickly.
- Branding and docs are not currently a reliable source of truth. The code is ahead of some repo-facing language.

