**Recent Routing Fix Note**
The latest behavioral repair was not a wording change. It was an ownership-order correction in [nova_http.py](nova_http.py).

The important rule is this:
- explicit PEIMS attendance handling must execute before generic planner/provider routing
- explicit developer-profile ownership must execute before generic planner/provider routing
- live device coordinates must win over saved location when Nova answers self-location questions

Why this matters:
- if `decide_actions(...)` or other generic provider selection runs first, turns that already have deterministic owners can be stolen by `web_research` or `wikipedia_lookup`
- that produces believable but wrong behavior because the explicit handler still exists, but it no longer owns the turn soon enough
- the real fix is seam ordering, not adding more phrase exceptions

Current lesson:
Nova behaves correctly when truth hierarchy and explicit intent ownership stay above generic planner/provider routing. If that order slips, identity, PEIMS, developer-profile, and location behavior regress even though the individual handlers are still present.

**Recent HTTP Extraction Note**
The next repair after the routing-order fix was structural: [process_chat](nova_http.py) had drifted back to owning the deterministic pre-reply routing block inline even though [services/nova_http_routing.py](services/nova_http_routing.py) already existed.

The important rule is this:
- an extraction is not real just because the service file exists
- the live shell must actually delegate to the shared service
- a seam test must enforce that delegation so the shell cannot quietly drift inline again

Why this matters:
- HTTP parity drifts when `nova_http.py` reassembles routing locally while CLI and runner paths keep using the shared contracts
- that kind of drift is easy to miss because behavior can still look mostly correct until a transport-specific regression appears
- the fix is wiring plus enforcement, not just creating a service module and assuming the extraction is complete

Current lesson:
Nova stays maintainable when shared routing contracts are both live and proven by tests. A dormant seam is not architecture; it is only another copy waiting to fork behavior later.

